<section xml:id="sec_coord_vec_summ">
  <title>Summary</title>
  <p>
    The key idea in this handout is the coordinate vector with respect to a basis.
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>\CB = \{\vv_1, \vv_2, \vv_3, \ldots, \vv_n\}</m> is a basis for a vector space <m>V</m>,
          then the coordinate vector of <m>\vx</m> in <m>V</m> with respect to <m>\CB</m> is the vector
          <me>
            [\vx]_{\CB} = [x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n]^{\tr}
          </me>,
          where
          <me>
            \vx = x_1 \vv_1 + x_2 \vv_2 + \cdots + x_n \vv_n
          </me>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The coordinate transformation
          <m>\vx \mapsto [\vx]_{\CB}</m> is a one-to-one and onto transformation from an <m>n</m>-dimensional vector space <m>V</m> to <m>\R^n</m> which preserves linear combinations.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The coordinate transformation
          <m>\vx \mapsto [\vx]_{\CB}</m> allows us to translate problems in arbitrary vector spaces to <m>\R^n</m> where we have already developed tools to solve the problems.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
</section>